
Variables are immutable by default, so 'let a = 1;' would be immutable. 'let mut b = 2;' would create a mutable variable.

Standard io stuff can be included from the standard library with 'use std::io;' to introduce shorthand. Using 'std::io::stdin()' would also work.

On 'stdin()', we can call '.read_line(&mut variable)'. & indicates the argument is by reference, and mut is needed because references are immutable by default.

This read function returns a Result. It is a union type of Ok(T) and Err(E). Running the code without doing anything with this is possible, but the compiler gives a warning that the Result may be an Err variant.
This can be handled with '.expect("Some message")', which returns the Ok value or raises a panic with the provided message. I feel like panics should be treated as a more severe version of an Exception. It might be possible to 'catch' it in some way, but this should probably not be done in general.

It is possible to 'fstring' with curly braces, both the inline and the argument approach. I feel like for pattern matching, globalization, and legibility, it would be preferable to use the arguments approach.

There work normally:
    'println!("Input: {}", input);'
    'println!("Input: {input}");'

But
    'println!("Input: {}", &input);'
works fine while
    'println!("Input: {&input}");'
doesn't compile.

Rust has variable shadowing, so you can just reuse existing variable names. I guess its fine for several steps manipulating a core variable, but outside of that case it would just hurt readability.
Parsing the input as a number and printing it shows me that the initially read string keeps the newline, so that's something to take into account.

Rust has full static type inference, so type annotations might be required at times, though I'll probably add them most of the time. I guess it's a bit of a var situation where I'd omit them in obvious situations.

Instead of expect, it's possible to directly switch on the types;

```
.parse() {
    Ok(v) => v,
    Err(_) => panic!("FIRE!"),
};
```


